<dl id="n53050i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53050i">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53050i"> 50(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> yesterday other day <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53050i"><li>FW 598.10 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/lexta.htm#n53050i">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/l39ta.htm#n53050i">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53050i">MS BL 47488-49v</ms> </li><li>JJA 63:050 <a name="tad3" href="../../FF/fdra/tda.htm#tad3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ta/tad3.htm#n53050i">Draft: IV&sect;1.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[More complicated is the case of the word &lsquo;<mark>yesterday</mark>&rsquo;, [German <i>gestern</i>]</font> cognate with Latin and Greek words which already denote &lsquo;the day before&rsquo;. In Germanic languages, however, &lsquo;yesterday&rsquo; &hellip; denoted <mark><i>the other day</i></mark>, that is, tomorrow as well. Later on, the use of the &lsquo;other day before&rsquo; replaced the other meaning in German, English, and Dutch.] <small> Fritz Mauthner, <a name="FMBK1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FMBK1"><cite title="source">Beitr&auml;ge zu einer Kritik der Sprache.</cite></a> 3 vols (1901-2) III 122</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
